acceptOwnership().details: New owner pending to accept ownership executes this function to confirm his ownership.

allowance(address,address).details: Returns the amount of tokens approved by the owner that can be transferred to the spender's account

params.spender: Address of spender that token owner approved to spend on his behalf
params.tokenOwner: Address of token owner we check for allowance on

approve(address,uint256).details: Token owner can approve for `spender` to transferFrom(...) `tokens` from the token owner's account 	 * https://github.com/ethereum/EIPs/blob/master/EIPS/eip-20-token-standard.md https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-20 recommends that there are no checks for the approval double-spend attack as this should be implemented in user interfaces

params.spender: Spender address user approves to spend tokens on his behalf
params.tokens: Amount of tokens spender is approved to spend/transfer

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller.      * This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}.      * Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance.      * Requirements:      * - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

depositAccept(address,uint256).details: Function executed by admin, after funds were received by bank wire or any other accepted method, admin deposits equal tokens to user address.

params._amount: Amount of tokens to deposit to user address
params._to: User address to deposit tokens to

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller.      * This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}.      * Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance.      * Requirements:      * - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

kill().details: Destroy contract eliminating it from the blockchain

reclaimEther(address).details: Send all eth balance in the contract to another address

params._to: Address to send contract ether balance to

recoverAnyERC20Token(address,uint256).details: Owner can transfer out any accidentally sent ERC20 tokens

params.tokenAddress: Token contract address we want to recover lost tokens from.
params.tokens: Amount of tokens to be recovered, usually the same as the balance of this contract.

transfer(address,uint256).details: Transfer the balance from token owner's account to `to` account - Owner's account must have sufficient balance to transfer - 0 value transfers are allowed

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: Transfer `tokens` from the `from` account to the `to` account 	 * The calling account must already have sufficient tokens approve(...)-d for spending from the `from` account and - From account must have sufficient balance to transfer - Spender must have sufficient allowance to transfer - 0 value transfers are allowed *** The user executing the function pays the transfer fees, not the funds owner

params.from: Address approved spender tranfers tokens from
params.tokens: Amount of tokens approved to transfer

params._newOwner: New owner address acquiring ownership of contract

withdrawRequest(uint256).details: Function executed by user asking for a withdrawal, withdrawal fee (if any) is substracted from withdrawal amount e.g. if user withdraws $1000 he pays $1 from that amount as fee (for withdrawal fee = 0.1%)

wipeoutAddressBalance(address).notice: *** BlockchainBridge contract functions *** BlacklistOperations contract functions
